11/01/2004
BERLIN, Germany -- Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan said Friday (9 January) that 2004 would be the year of reform for his government. 
Addressing a forum of Turkish and German businessmen, he announced that he has "declared war on three things: poverty, corruption and bans on civil liberties".Erdogan pledged to carry out the reforms in time for the EU summit at the end of the year.
In other news, Turkey's Permanent Representative to the Council of Europe signed Protocol 13 of the European Convention on Human Rights, which requires countries to observe the ban on the death penalty in all circumstances, including wartime or danger of war. 
A European Commission spokesman said this was "a further significant step for Turkey on its way to becoming a full-fledged democracy, fully respecting European standards for human rights". 
(Anadolu Agnecy, AFP - 09/01/04)
